.\" vim: tw=75
.TH svstat 8
.SH NAME
svstat \- print status of services monitored by \fBsupervise\fR(8).

.SH SYNOPSIS
\fBsvstat\fR \fIservices\fR

.SH DESCRIPTION
\fIservices\fR consists of any number of arguments, each argument naming a
directory. \fBsvstat\fR prints one human-readable line for each directory,
saying whether \fBsupervise\fR(8) is successfully running in that
directory, and reporting the status and process information maintained by
\fBsupervise\fR. The information printed is the \fBstatus\fR and \fBpid\fR.
The \fBstatus\fR is one of \fIup\fR, \fIdown\fR or \fIwait\fR. In case the
service status is \fIup\fR, \fBpid\fR is the process id of the service. In
case the status is either \fIdown\fR or \fIwait\fR, \fBpid\fR will be the
process id of the \fBsupervise\fR process.

.EX
# this service is up. here the pid of qmail-qmtpd is 762703
$ svstat /service/qmail-qmtpd.209
/service/qmail-qmtpd.209: up 64849.402144999 seconds pid 762703

# this service is down. here the pid of supervise is 762596
$ svstat /service/qmail-qmqpd.628
/service/qmail-qmqpd.628: down 3453.701675999 seconds spid 762596

# this service is waiting for a dependent service to be up
# It has been waiting for the past 96 seconds. The pid
# 762630 is the pid of the supervise process
$ svstat /service/inlookup.infifo
/service/inlookup.infifo: wait 96.530758999 seconds spid 762630

# this service has already waited 3.28 seconds since a dependent
# service came up. It will further wait for 7 seconds. The pid
# 762630 is the pid of the supervise process
$ svstat /service/inlookup.infifo
/service/inlookup.infifo: wait 3.285475999 seconds spid 762630 remaining 7 seconds
.EE

If the argument to \fBsvscan\fR names just one directory, then the return
value will reflect various status of a service as below

.EX
	 111 - system error
	 100 - bad status
	   0 - service running
	   1 - service down
	   2 - supervise not running
	   3 - service paused
	   4 - down - wants up
	   5 - up   - wants down
	   6 - wait - wating for service to come up
.EE

